<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-347-170  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 347 170.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  April 16 1990 n363 p24(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Russian language MS-DOS debuts.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Clancy, Heather.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microsoft Corp introduces a Russian language version of MS-DOSversion 4.01.andP;  The version for the Soviet market brings the numberof foreign-language editions of the operating system to 13.andP;  Thenew version of MS-DOS uses a Cyrillic character set for theon-screen display, and it supports printers and output deviceswith Cyrillic fonts.andP;  Menus, dialog boxes and online help filesall appear in Russian.andP;  Microsoft claims the operating system willhelp standardize Soviet computing and will allow Soviet users totake advantage of the wide array of applications available forMS-DOS.andP;  Microsoft claims one of the difficulties on the Sovietmarket place is the lack of copyright laws, and the piracy thatensues.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   MS-DOS 4.01 (Operating system) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Russian LanguageOperating SystemsStandardizationSoviet UnionLanguage Translation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>